Why Jerome Powell must go
NEW YORK – US President Joe Biden faces a critical decision: Who should he appoint as head of the US Federal Reserve – essentially to the possibly most powerful position within the global economy?
A wrong decision here can have far-reaching consequences.
Under Alan Greenspan and Ben Bernanke, the Fed failed to adequately regulate the banking system, thereby laying the groundwork for the worst global economic downturn in 75 years.
This crisis and the reaction of the political decision-makers to it had far-reaching political consequences; they exacerbated inequality and nurtured a lasting sense of discontent among those who lost their homes and jobs.
There is a variety of clichés as to why current Federal Reserve Chairman Jerome Powell should be reconfirmed.
It would be a proof of non-partisanship.
It would strengthen the credibility of the Fed.
Someone with experience would be used, who would lead us through the recovery in the wake of the pandemic.
And so on.
Exactly the same arguments I heard 25 years ago, when I was chairman of the economic advisory board of US President Bill Clinton, and Greenspan's confirmation to the post was an issue.
They were enough to convince Clinton, and the country paid dearly for his decision.
Ironically, President Ronald Reagan paid little attention to these arguments as he effectively fired Paul Volcker in 1987 and denied him a second term after Volcker had tamed inflation.
Reagan owed much to Volcker, but he sought deregulation and therefore chose Greenspan, an Ayn Rand follower.
In economic policy, careful assessment and sensitivity for conflicting goals are required.
How important is inflation in comparison to jobs and growth?
How confident can we be that markets are efficient, stable, fair, and shaped by competition on their own?
How concerned should we be about inequality?
The two major parties in the US always held clearly differing, but clearly articulated views on these issues (at least until the Republicans fell prey to populist delusions).
From my point of view, Democrats are right to worry about the consequences of unemployment.
The 2008 crisis has shown that unregulated markets are neither efficient nor stable.
In addition, we know that traditionally, only in times of tense labor markets, marginalized groups are brought into the economy and wage differences are reduced.
The coming years may pose a test of endurance for every US Federal Reserve chief.
The US is already being confronted with difficult decisions on what to do about inflation.
Are the latest price increases essentially small problems stemming from an unprecedented economic shutdown?
How should the Fed view the unemployment rate of African Americans, which has not yet recovered to its pre-pandemic level?
Would interest rate hikes (and the accompanying increase in unemployment) be worse than the disease itself as a remedy?
Equally important: While the mispricing of mortgage-backed securities played a central role in the 2008 crisis, there are now indications of an even stronger and more pervasive mispricing associated with assets related to climate change.
What should the Fed do in this regard?
Powell is not the man of the hour.
Initially, he supported the deregulation agenda of former President Donald Trump and thereby risked the financial health of our world.
And he still hesitates to take action regarding climate risk, although other central bankers around the world have meanwhile declared it the central problem of the coming decades.
Powell would argue that climate issues don't fall within the Fed's mandate, but that would be wrong.
It is part of the Fed's mandate to ensure financial stability, and there is no greater threat to financial stability than climate change.
The Fed is also responsible for approving mergers in the financial sector, and Powell's record suggests he has never experienced a bad merger.
Such laxity is the last thing the economy needs right now.
A blatant lack of competition and the absence of sufficient regulation already enable excessive profits, reduce lending to small businesses and give dominant actors more scope to exploit others.
Some commentators credit Powell with the Fed's response to the pandemic.
However, every second-year student would have known that during a recession, you can't tighten monetary policy and raise interest rates.
And as Simon Johnson of MIT argued, Powell does not feel particularly committed to full employment.
In contrast, Powell's record as a member of the US Federal Reserve Board, in terms of tightening monetary policy, was marked by a series of misjudgments over the past decade, which date back to the "Taper Tantrum" of 2013.
Although many Fed observers insist that inequality is not the central bank's concern, it is a fact that the bank's policy has significant distributional effects that cannot be ignored.
Just as an early tightening of interest rates can choke off growth, allowing a weak enforcement of the Community Reinvestment Act can enable stronger concentrations of market power.
And lastly, the latest scandal over stock trading by senior Fed officials has eroded trust in the leadership of the central bank.
Powell's apparent lack of awareness of conflicts of interest, including the management of some Fed programs in response to the pandemic, has been concerning me for a long time.
After four years of Trump weakening trust in US institutions, there is now a real risk that trust in the central bank's integrity will suffer further.
No Fed representative should need an ethics officer to decide when certain market transactions would appear unseemly.
The Fed bears certain similarities to the US Supreme Court.
This is intended to be above politics, but at least since Bush v. Gore we know that is not the case.
Trump has made it clear for all those who still had doubts.
The Fed is supposed to be independent, however, Powell and Greenspan have clearly shown that this is also not the case by following their party's deregulation agenda.
However, while the central bank board makes important decisions that affect all aspects of the economy, traditionally the power lies in the hands of the central bank chief - and that much more strongly than with the Chief Justice of the Supreme Court.
It is the central bank chief who decides what comes to a vote and which topics are delayed or pushed through.
The climate question is just an example of where it's extremely important who sits at the head of the table.
The US needs a central bank that truly commits to overseeing a stable, fair, efficient, and competitive financial sector.
Those who believe we can rely on unbridled markets or that regulation is too far-reaching already lack perspective.
We neither need an ideologue like Greenspan nor a lawyer inclined to Wall Street like Powell.
Someone with a deep understanding of macroeconomics and who shares Biden's values and worries about inflation and unemployment is needed.
There are undoubtedly a lot of people who meet these conditions.
But Biden doesn't have to look far to find someone who has already proven his abilities.
Lael Brainard is already on the central bank board, where she has demonstrated her expertise and earned the trust of the markets - without compromising on her values.
Biden can have both: a central bank chief who preserves continuity and does not unsettle the markets, but shares his economic and social program.
